      cellularDetail: "Like all benzodiazepines, diazepam binds to the α/γ subunit interface of GABA-A receptors and increases the frequency of chloride channel opening in response to GABA binding. Diazepam is pharmacologically distinguished by three features: (1) High lipophilicity: diazepam rapidly crosses the blood-brain barrier, producing onset within 1-5 minutes IV. However, its high lipophilicity also causes rapid redistribution from brain into adipose tissue, which terminates the initial CNS effect faster than its elimination half-life would predict. (2) Active metabolites: diazepam is hepatically metabolized via CYP2C19 and CYP3A4 to desmethyldiazepam (nordiazepam, half-life 36-200 hours), oxazepam, and temazepam: all pharmacologically active. This creates an effective duration of action that can exceed 200 hours in elderly patients with reduced hepatic function. (3) Muscle relaxation: diazepam enhances GABA-A activity in spinal interneurons that mediate presynaptic inhibition of motor neurons, reducing muscle tone and spasm through supraspinal and spinal mechanisms.",
